Shader-Based Renewable Energy Farm Visualization
=================================================

Author: Gunabhiram Aruru
Course: CSCI 4229/5229 Computer Graphics

Project Overview
----------------
This final project is an interactive compatibility-profile OpenGL renewable
energy farm. The startup view immediately shows the complete facility with
textures, lighting, animated turbines, wind-flow ribbons, transparent
greenhouse glass, solar generation, battery storage, a substation, a control
building, a weather station, and a small sheep paddock. Distance fog is
available but is off by default so the full scene is clear at launch.

Build and Run
-------------
Run from this directory:

    make
    ./final

Remove generated build products with:

    make clean

The default build uses:

    g++ -std=c++11 -Wall -Wextra

On Linux, GLUT/OpenGL development packages are required. GLEW can optionally
be enabled with:

    make USEGLEW=1

Controls
--------

    0                 Show the complete farm
    1                 Inspect one wind turbine
    2                 Inspect the barn / farmhouse
    3                 Inspect the greenhouse
    4                 Inspect one solar panel
    5                 Inspect the battery / inverter unit
    6                 Inspect one sheep
    7                 Inspect the farmer / maintenance worker
    8                 Inspect a handmade boulder cluster
    Left mouse drag   Rotate in orbit and first-person modes
    Mouse wheel       Change orbit distance (orbit mode only)
    Arrow keys        Rotate in orbit and first-person modes
    W / S             Move forward/backward (first-person mode only)
    A / D             Strafe left/right (first-person mode only)
    PageUp/PageDown   Change orbit distance (orbit mode only)
    + or =            Decrease orbit distance
    - or _            Increase orbit distance
    m                 Cycle orbit, first-person, and fixed overhead cameras
    R                 Reset to the default full-scene view
    r                 Pause/resume turbine blades
    [ and ]           Decrease/increase shared wind speed
    v or V            Toggle wind ribbon visibility
    p or P            Toggle GLSL wind shader/fixed-pipeline fallback
    Space             Pause/resume automatic sun movement
    , and .           Move the sun angle manually
    < and >           Lower/raise the sun
    l or L            Toggle lighting
    f or F            Toggle distance fog
    t or T            Toggle textures
    g or G            Toggle greenhouse glass
    a or A            Toggle axes outside first-person mode; A strafes left
                      while in first-person mode
    q, Q, or ESC      Exit

Object Inspection Mode
----------------------
Keys 1 through 8 isolate one major object at the world origin over a neutral
grid. Each mode uses a dedicated orbit-camera preset and retains orbit rotation
and distance controls. First-person movement updates the camera's world
position; the fixed overhead camera provides a top-down review. This makes
geometry, normals, materials, animation, and silhouette easy to inspect
without surrounding-scene occlusion. Key 0 returns to the complete farm.

Handmade Objects
----------------
All scene models are constructed from course-appropriate primitives and
handwritten vertices; no imported 3D models are used.

- Three instanced wind turbines with handmade tapered towers and rotor blades
- Nine solar-panel assemblies with supports, frames, and cell dividers
- Battery/inverter storage shed with textured walls and roof, three internal
  battery cabinets, emissive status LEDs, side inverter, and output conduit
- Electrical substation with transformers, gantries, insulators, and wiring
- Transparent greenhouse with frame, door, roof, plant beds, and crop rows
- Renewable-energy control building with windows, sign, rooftop box, and antenna
- Weather station with sensor box, wind vane, anemometer, and small solar panel
- Fenced paddock with four instanced low-poly sheep and a water trough
- Stylized maintenance worker with hard hat, safety vest, and work boots
- Terrain, crop rows, roads, fences, signs, trees, textured boulders, and
  utility poles

Original Contribution
---------------------
The primary original contribution is the coupled GLSL wind-flow visualization.
Twelve handmade transparent quad strips cross the turbine field. One shared
`windSpeed` value controls turbine rotor speed, weather-station anemometer
speed, and wind-ribbon travel, making the visual airflow and physical scene
animation respond together.

The contribution also includes shader loading and diagnostics, uniform
management, fixed-pipeline fallback rendering, transparent render ordering,
expanded facility layout, object inspection modes, and the integration of
animated farm characters with renewable-energy equipment.

Shader Wind Visualization
-------------------------
`wind.vert` and `wind.frag` use GLSL 1.20 syntax. The vertex shader receives
`time` and `windSpeed`, then applies small sine-wave displacement to ribbon
vertices. The fragment shader produces a subtle blue-white alpha pulse and
supports the scene's optional linear fog.

Ribbons are rendered after opaque geometry with blending enabled, depth testing
left enabled, and depth writes disabled. If shader loading, compilation, or
linking fails, the same geometry is animated on the CPU and drawn through the
fixed pipeline. Press `p` to switch between GLSL and the fallback, and press
`v` to control ribbon visibility independently.

Transparency and Lighting
-------------------------
Opaque scene geometry is drawn first. Wind ribbons and greenhouse glass are
drawn afterward with source-alpha blending and temporary depth-write
suppression. Depth testing remains active, and normal depth writes are restored
after each transparent pass.

A moving positional light represents the sun. Solar panels use strong
specular highlights; batteries, turbines, and substation equipment use medium
metal highlights; the control building and wood details are mostly diffuse;
glass uses a restrained transparent highlight; sheep and worker materials are
matte. The shared box, roof, turbine, tree, and ellipsoid geometry supplies
explicit normals, while `GL_NORMALIZE` handles transformed geometry.

Texture Mapping and Credits
---------------------------
Textures are assigned by material type and repeated with object-scale texture
coordinates to avoid obvious stretching. Grass is reserved for terrain, path
for roads, metal for energy equipment, roof for building roofs, and wood for
doors, signs, and fences.

The following reference textures were supplied by a friend and are used only
where they fit the renewable-farm theme:

- `bark.bmp` on tree trunks
- `leaves.bmp` on low-poly tree canopies
- `rock.bmp` on handmade boulders
- `wall.bmp` on the control building walls

Other available reference textures were intentionally not included because
they duplicated existing materials, did not map cleanly to the low-detail
geometry, or did not fit the project theme. All 3D geometry and texture
coordinates remain handwritten for this project.

Code Reuse and AI Assistance
----------------------------
This project builds on my HW2/HW3 camera, projection, lighting, texture-loading,
and scene foundation. Course examples were referenced for projection, lighting,
textures, transparency, fog, and shader setup.

AI assistance was used for planning, debugging, refactoring suggestions,
README wording, and small code patterns. I reviewed and modified the final code
and am responsible for understanding it.

My main new contributions are the expanded renewable-energy farm, object
inspection modes, turbine/wind interaction, shader-based wind ribbon
visualization with a fixed-pipeline fallback, transparency, fog, lighting
controls, and integration.

No class example source files or HW2/HW3 submission files are included in the
final submission folder.

New for the Final Project
-------------------------

- Expanded 90-by-90 farm with distinct connected energy zones
- Reusable inspection modes for eight requested major-object categories
- Solar farm, battery yard, substation, and visible electrical network
- Upgraded control building with facility sign and rooftop equipment
- Transparent greenhouse with correct opaque/transparent draw ordering
- Weather station coupled to the shared wind-speed model
- Four varied sheep instances with a restrained idle head bob
- Static maintenance worker positioned at the battery shed
- Instanced textured boulders along paths and in two restrained landscape clusters
- GLSL wind ribbons plus animated fixed-pipeline fallback
- Shared wind-speed controls and expanded status HUD
- Moving sun marker and object-specific material polish
- Optional fog, disabled by default

Known Limitations
-----------------

- The project uses legacy compatibility-profile OpenGL, GLUT, and GLSL 1.20.
- Transparent panels are ordered by object pass rather than sorted per polygon.
- Wind ribbons visualize airflow but do not simulate fluid dynamics.
- Sheep are decorative fixed placements rather than simulated agents.
- First-person movement has no collision detection.
- Bitmap text and texture paths require running the executable from this folder.
- Textures are uncompressed 24-bit power-of-two BMP files.

Time Spent
----------
Time Spent: Approximately 37 hours, including reuse/refactoring from HW2/HW3,
shader integration, object modeling, debugging, README cleanup, and final
testing.

